How to survive a heatwave advice from Australia. When we have days that reach 45 degrees celsius we keep all blinds and windows shut. This just adds another layer/barrier and stops the sun from heating up the air within the house, that way your house stays much cooler !! Also have a cold shower before bed and get straight into bed, tripping wet. Takes the edge of when your trying to go to sleep, plus it feels amazing when the fan air brushed pass.

For Stand up Paddle Boarding AKA SUP Boarding: To help with balancing try to keep your knees slightly bent at all times and have your weight forward a bit. Also, someone said it already but either take smaller movements when moving to standing up, like kneel and then put one foot up and then the other or I crouch down and get my weight in the right place and then slowly stand or start standing up from the shore. This will give you a longer time to balance when in shallow water. I hope this helps you Zoe or anyone else wanting help with SUP boarding

As someone from the US who has spent a lot of time in the U.K. I always have to wonder....why don't people just start installing AC? I understand the history, the culture, I know it's not common inside most buildings especially older ones. And I know there are more years than not where it hasn't been needed because the summers are super mild.

BUT....

I think it's probably due to climate change but for the past several years, every summer, everyone keeps saying it's "unusually hot" for the U.K. Hot many years before it's no longer called unusual? And why don't people who are fairly well off (like Zoe and Alfie) and who gut/ renovate their homes (like they did with this one) simply install AC units? Why just keep putting up with it? They have an AGA, they have a tap that always produces boiling water, but no AC? Why wasn't it considered? Is it because it's not easy to do/ get from contractors? I know in the US since the 80s a really common small business was heat/ AC installation and repair. Right up there with plumbers. Is it so much harder in the U.K.?

I love rainy days, however I am really scared of thunderstorms (I have autism and panic attacks) anyone got any tips on how to get over my fear

When I have panic attacks I try to do this thing called grounding (I think) where I try to identify 5 things I can see, hear, smell and touch. I feel like it just really helps to calm me down if I focus on things other than the panic attack itself. Maybe you could cut out the part where you think of what you can hear if thunder makes you anxious or you could try to listen out for 5 other sounds and focus on them instead. I know it’s so much easier said than done and not everything works for everyone but I go over each thing in my head until I’ve calmed down and sometimes I find new things to focus on. Hope you find something that helps you if this doesn’t x
